I Contain Multitudes

by Wonaglot

 Prologue.

You awaken in the crew quarters, hanging halfway off your miserable bed and feeling the damp in your bones. Your head throbs with a host of strange images and regrets. Though you cannot remember last night, you have every reason to expect you went about your normal business and spent your off hours carving one of your sculptures.

The door creaks open and Captain Bosch enters, looking quite out of place all the way down in the lower decks where you, an assistant engineer, spend your free hours on the ship of dreams.

"Chandra. My quarters. I have something to discuss with you."

You attend the captain in his quarters. You don't often go above deck, and the brief moments of light and the crisp sea air are a welcome panacea for your addled mind.

The captain walks to his desk and removes a rare cigar, cuts the tip, and lights it.

"Did you know the bishop was found early this morning?"

1: Yes
2: No

You are in the Captain's Cabin.
You can see a Walnut Desk and Captain Bosch.
You can go northwest.

The smell of the crisp sea air and light from the windows penetrates into the luxurious room. The captain's cabin is characterized by cherrywood paneling and a wax-shined wooden floor with a rug that squishes beneath your feet. There is the sort of elegance here that juxtaposes the captain's brusque manner, though his love for reading is apparent in the bookshelves built into the wall. A large bed sits on one side of the room, while the captain's desk and plush, upholstered chair occupies the other. There is a globe in a wooden cabinet with clawed feet in the corner.

The exit to the Navigation Deck is to the northwest.
> 2

"No."

"Of course not. How could you?"

He takes a long inhale on his cigar and when he exhales, the smoke completely obscures his face for a moment.

"Everyone assumes he fell overboard, but that wasn't what killed him. Early this morning, one of the crew found him. He spied a rope hanging over the starboard edge, which appeared to be dragging something. After a few of the men pulled it up, they discovered it was a body, whom the doctor identified as the bishop. I have no doubt in my mind that he was murdered. As this is a delicate matter, I want you to quietly investigate the ship for any signs of foul play. This ship is a virgin, and I'll not have the spectre of an unsolved death on her first voyage."

An indistinct smile, smoke leaking through yellowed teeth, and a thick moustache.

"I expect you have questions."

1: Why me?
2: How long do I have?
3: Where do I begin?
> 2

"How long do I have?"

"A wise question. Since the body was found I set a course for the nearest port. Tralta is roughly an hour away. When we arrive, the authorities will deal with the body--and the murderer, if they are found."

His eyes drift over you like flotsam.

"If you are finished before we arrive, you may come to me at any time to end your investigation and report."

1: Why me?
2: Where do I begin?
> 2

"Where do I begin?"

The captain scratches his moustache with his thick, yellowed fingernails.

"Perhaps your belongings down in the crew quarters may be of some use to you. After that, well, you have your run of the ship. There are a number of distinguished passengers on board; if you question them, I urge you to do your utmost to be discrete. You don't want to end up like the bishop, do you?"

"And why me?"

The captain's features harden briefly and he taps his cigar into an glass ashtray on the desk.

"Because I have a ship to run. Since you're a junior crew member on your first posting, you have everything to lose if you break my trust. Therefore, I expect you to be discrete. We all know you're the one with the answers."

"I'm going back to the helm. Begin as soon as you can. And get out of my cabin."

He stamps out his cigar and ushers you out of the room, back to the crew quarters.

If it is your first time playing, type HELP for some friendly advice.

You are in The Crew Quarters.
You can see a Hungry Devil Mask, a Blithe Cherub Mask, a Weeping Widow Mask, an Anonymous Bauta and a Footlocker.
You can go east.

The crew quarters is a sparse cavern of a room full of uncomfortable bunk beds. This is where the crew sleeps and relaxes; metal tables for the tawdry sort of card games the passengers in the upper decks wouldn't think of playing, and the smell of rye is thick in the air. You can hear the discomfiting lullaby of the engine through the wall, and the Prinzessin creaks and groans as she fords through the sea. There are several third shift crewmembers in the room, sleeping off the morning gin. At the foot of each bed is an unassuming crew footlocker full of personal belongings, and one of your sculptures is sitting out on your bed.

East leads to the Lower Deck.

Four masks laid neatly out on your bed are all whispering to each other when you enter the room. When you see draw close to them, they all stop sharply.

There she is....
