You are in The Lower Deck.
You can go west, east, north, south or up.

The lower deck lacks the ostentatious displays of architecture and the niceties of the life of the gentry. Here, there are only slats of hard oak floor and metal walls painted white with blue stripes along the corners near the floor to guide the crew about. Brass intercom phones sit on the walls and crackle to life when orders come down from the bridge.

You can go back up the stairs to the mid deck. North leads to the brig, and south to the engine room. Your quarters are due west, and the ship's storage is to the east.
> up

> up

You are in Mid Deck.
You can see Charlotte Wistemmen.
You can go down, up, south, southwest, west, east or southeast.

The mid deck is swathed in the most opulent materials, as many of the illustrious passengers spend their recreational time here. The walls are covered in gilded boiserie and thick crimson carpet cushions the linoleum hallways. Windows covered by velvet curtains look out onto the sea, and above the staircase leading to the upper decks hangs a grand portrait of the Prizessin Anna Alexia herself, the girl after whom the ship is named.

Going up or down will lead to the upper and lower decks, respectively. To the west is the Library, while the Dark Room for guests to develop photographs sits in the south west. To the east is gymnasium, and the game parlor occupies a room off the south east corridor. Finally, the rooms of the ship's staff such as the maids, the chefs, and so on, is located to the south.
> talk charlotte

> talk charlotte

"Hello there," Charlotte says softly. She appears to have been wandering the corridors in a dissociative state. "Are you a crew member?"

"I am. Name's Chandra Fitz."

"I'm Charlotte, Charlotte Wistemmen. This may be unexpected, but, will you listen to my woes? I need an impartial ear now more than ever."

1: Yes
2: No
> 1

The ghost of a smile haunts Charlotte's lips.

"Thank you. I have been ruminating on my disembowelment, which thrust me halfway into the next world. You see, my father is the Earl of Wore, a withered man whose constitution is failing him. Yet, his unfeigned derision toward me is endless. He does not approve of my marrying outside the country, as he is of an insular mind."

"The reason you see me, translucent and incorporeal with my inner woes adorning my frame like tears from the moon, is due to the actions of my father. One month ago he had my horses driven into the sea!"

To even recall this fact brings a lachrymosal quaver to her voice.

"Every one of them gone! My loves, my darlings, for whom I so dutifully cared! All lost in the same heartless sea that carries this ship. Oh, to think of it! I require something to calm my nerves. A medicine, panacea for these shadows before my eyes. You, will you fetch me something? Anything."

1: Of course.
> 1

"Of course. I'll find something to help you."

"Oh, dear one! Please hurry. I shall wait for you in the game parlor. The sound of shuffling cards soothes my rampant mind."

Charlotte offers you a forced smile, then she is on her way.
> up

> up

You are in The Upper Deck.
You can go down, up, north, northeast, south or in.

The upper decks of the Prinzessin contain lavish entertainment venues for the passengers. Parquet floors beneath carpet and paneled walls decorated with paintings and portholes line the corridors, and giddy passengers with seemingly infinite energy and wealth titter as they jostle past you.

A grand archway in the middle of the deck leads to the main dining area and the kitchens beyond that, where guests can dine in privacy or lavishly with enormous parties. North and northwest lie the sickbay and the saloon, respectively, as if one was meant to service the other. To the south you'll get lost in the passageways leading to the passengers' quarters, and going up or down the stairs will lead you to the weather deck and fresh air, or deeper into the stomach of the ship.
> ne

> ne

You are in The Saloon.
You can see Arania Kowser.
You can go southwest.

In some ways, the saloon is the heart of the cruise ship, or at least the liver. This is where passengers can obtain libations and carouse with each other--doubtless there are a great number of world-shaking alliances being made in this room. It is two stories, with an upper floor filled with secluded tables, chairs, and booths upholstered in red velvet. Wait staff mill about the guests and all but ignore you once they take a look at your clothes. The crew is not allowed to make use of any of the guest facilities.

Going through the varnished double doors to the southwest will take you back to the upper deck's hallways.
> order a drink

> order a drink

You inquire with the bartender about a drink and he winks charitably at you. "For one of the crew, it's on the house. Just don't go getting too screwed, eh? You finish this bottle and there won't be enough hard tack and coffee to keep you standing."

The bartender hands you a half-empty bottle of whisky.
> talk arania

> talk arania

"Well, hello, my dear," Arania coos as she sets down her seltzer. "Are you one of the crew? Thirsty work, I imagine."

"I'm not here to quench thirst, madame."

 "Oh?" she smiles and brandishes her white teeth like a shield. "I'm Arania Kowser, singer. Well, I'm a little more than that. But before I go carrying on, let me ask you something. How's your singing voice?"

1: Not the worst, nor the best.
> 1

"Now the worst, not the best."

"My dear, modesty suits audience members, not performers. I am calling on you to assist me in the recitation of my lines. My libretto, it is in the library. We will take it to my suite and we will sing, so that when we return to shore, the understudy will weep. She thinks I am resting my voice," she laughs in a soprano's sharp pitch, "yet I am greasing the stiletto, yes? Go on, go, go go little canary, return promptly! La prima donna does not wait!"
