You are in The Dining Room.
You can see Hartleford Kowser.
You can go out or west.

A chandelier sparkles above you, and a domed ceiling allows a view of foreboding gray sky. Despite the coming storm, the dining room remains steadfastly decadent, with statues welcoming guests into a host of tables, booths, and bar space. Although there are some private dining rooms tables sequestered behind carved wood columns, most of the seating is located in a large central space, lowered two steps to give the wait staff a vantage as they circumnavigate the sea of ravenous guests.

No one will make eye contact with you, but you can feel their eyes on you when your back is turned.

Heading out will bring you back to the Upper Deck. The kitchens lie west.
> talk hartleford

> talk hartleford

"Good day to you," he replies. "Are you a crewmember? How fascinating. Judging by those coveralls, I'd wager you spend more time below decks than above. It's just as well, I had something on my mind and speaking to a stranger about it might provide insightful. Tell me, if I have my sights on a beautiful young lady but she does not know of my existence, is it untoward to send her a letter? I shall sign my name, of course."

1: Who doesn't love an unexpected letter from an admirer?
> 1

"Who doesn't love an unexpected letter from an admirer?"

"Perhaps you are correct. No endeavor can yield fruit without first planting the seed. Very well. In a few minutes, meet me in the library, if you would. I could use your apparently vast wisdom to help me compose the letter."

With that, Hartleford picks up and leaves.

Hartleford must be waiting for you in the library by now.
