You are in a The Library.
You can see a Libretto and Hartleford Kowser.
You can go east.

The library is silent save for the churning of the ocean beneath the vessel. You have never seen so many books, stacked on high shelves inlaid with brass plaques indicating their alphabetical organization. Shadows consume the corners of the room, and glass-hooded desk lamps are all there are to light the spaces between the stacks. The curtains are drawn and it is difficult to read the titles of the books, or the expressions of those passengers hunched over them. Out of the corner of your eye, their faces are a mix of misplaced features.

One librarian curates the entire collection. She is sitting at a desk poring over a mail-order catalogue.
