You are in The Passenger Quarters.
You can go north, Suite One Door, Suite Three Door, Suite Four Door or Suite Two Door.

A long series of hallways studded with dark wooden doors with golden knobs. Endless lines of white plaster orac moulding sweeps down the corners of the ceiling. These corridors lead to the rooms of the passengers, each as opulent as on a royal yacht. You find yourself wondering how much these individual rooms cost for the duration of the cruise. Each door has a number, though the doors are not unique in and of themselves. There is no way to tell them apart.

Heading north will lead you back to the upper deck's main corridors.
> sw

> sw

You are in Suite Three.
You can see Arania Kowser.
You can go northeast.

This is a first class suite, as are all the suites on the upper deck. The interior can only be described as palatial: a bedroom and a drawing room have been provided with the sort of creature comforts wealthy guests tend to expect. Glistening light pours in from covered lamps and wall sconces. Sinks in wood cabinetry and a large bed occupy most of the space, along with the other furniture. Unlike the rooms in the lower decks, the first class suites were not constructed with restraint in mind. They sprawl compared to the closets below decks for the crew. Dark maroon pile-on-pile velvet curtains keep out the natural light of the day and elegant sofas and chairs with clutching lion feet seem poised to gambol across the carpet, which depicts a repeating pattern of a peacock's tailfan.
> talk arania

> talk arania

"Are you ready to begin?"

1: Yes
2: No
> 1

"Yes."

"Then, let us, in this room, dream of the stage, and live as the characters! Now then."

Arania closes her eyes. When she opens them, she has transformed. Her face, her gestures, and the slant of her body as she stands. She has become Lathea.

"Act one! The golden thread trails long behind Sisandrus and Lathea as they mark their path to the Temple of Altadeus.They come before a grand statue of the great deity, his mouth turned down in disgust."

Incredibly, she has memorized even the scene directions by heart.

At long last, Arania begins to sing. She is a soprano of the most profound ability, and her voice makes incredible leaps and trills as she passionate

"Here is your missing weaver! Judge him before you, not in blind absentia. You who battered and crushed the bones of my parents, lift your hand, so I can strike it off!"

There is a tear in your eye before she finishes the first sentence.

1: Wager not insult him again! Already my heart bursts with my falsity.
2: Venture not insult him alas! Already my heart  brims with my infelicity.
3: Venture not insult him again! Already, my heart breaks with my infidelity.
> 3

"Venture not insult him again! Already, my heart breaks with my infidelity."

Arania watches you expectantly.

"To war, even a weaver must go," you sing bravely.

1: Pry the spear from the enmity and with it tread his heart.
2: Pluck the sword from thine enemy and with it thread her heart.
3: Pluck the spear from the enemy and with it thread his heart.
> 3

"Pluck the spear from the enemy and with it thread his heart."

Lathea, or Arania, continues.

"Cowardice lies too in courage, when a man throws down his life for a cause so malefic as the curse cast when he kills another."

On cue, you shout, "Cowardice!" in shock and dismay.

"For he is too craven to find another way, be it more difficult than the stroke of his sword."

For a moment, both of you stand there catching your breath. Arania's enthusiasm is rather infectious, and her demeanor can make even the impersonal environment of a cruise ship seem comfortable, even safe, or at least diverting.

Arania rushes over to you, clapping vigorously, and seizes your hand in hers.

"How marvelous! You should consider a career in this! I would just adore working with you in a production. Now I feel as though I better understand the plight of Lathea. I still have troubles on land, but for now, I am pleased. Thank you for your assistance."
> talk arania

> talk arania

After the excitement of singing, Arania has calmed down, and sits on the plush couch playing thoughtfully with the ring on her left hand.

"Oh, my dear. There is something else that has been on my mind. You see, when I return to land, to my company, there is an understudy who has been plotting to kill me. I have seen the plans sketched and stuck behind the mirror of her dressing room. She is a bloodthirsty young thing, like so many others. Did you think death in opera only happens on the stage, and not behind it?"

Pausing to chuckle omniously, Arania turns head eyes up to you. They are clear as a running stream.

"I know I must either relinquish the role to save my life." After a moment of grim silence, she continues. "Or I could lay a trap for her. What do you think?"

1: Follow whatever sings loudest to you.
> 1

"Follow whatever sings loudest to you."

Arania, who had been holding her breath, exhales.

"You are right. I cannot have another make the decision for me. You have given me much to think about."
