You are in The Passenger Quarters.
You can go north, Suite One Door, Suite Three Door, Suite Four Door or Suite Two Door.

A long series of hallways studded with dark wooden doors with golden knobs. Endless lines of white plaster orac moulding sweeps down the corners of the ceiling. These corridors lead to the rooms of the passengers, each as opulent as on a royal yacht. You find yourself wondering how much these individual rooms cost for the duration of the cruise. Each door has a number, though the doors are not unique in and of themselves. There is no way to tell them apart.

Heading north will lead you back to the upper deck's main corridors.
> n

> n

You are in The Upper Deck.
You can go down, up, north, northeast, south or in.

The upper decks of the Prinzessin contain lavish entertainment venues for the passengers. Parquet floors beneath carpet and paneled walls decorated with paintings and portholes line the corridors, and giddy passengers with seemingly infinite energy and wealth titter as they jostle past you.

A grand archway in the middle of the deck leads to the main dining area and the kitchens beyond that, where guests can dine in privacy or lavishly with enormous parties. North and northwest lie the sickbay and the saloon, respectively, as if one was meant to service the other. To the south you'll get lost in the passageways leading to the passengers' quarters, and going up or down the stairs will lead you to the weather deck and fresh air, or deeper into the stomach of the ship.
> up

> up

You are in The Weather Deck.
You can go down, west or up.

The weather deck is the uppermost passenger deck, allowing for a comfortable stroll around the ship to take in the sea air. Hard slats of polished wood travel along the deck and circle the inner body of the ship. You can see into the upper decks from here through countless windows. Standing near the side, you can see the body of the Prinzessin, painted white as snow, and her richly decorated prow. Curls of hammered gold ornamentation wrap around the tip of the prow and just above them her name is engraved upon a decorated plate: Prinzessin Anna Alexia.
> up

> up

You are in The Navigation Deck.
You can go down, east or southeast.

The navigation deck sits above the weather deck to provide the bridge with a clear vantage point over the ocean in every direction. This is where the captain's cabin and the bridge are located. Vents allow air below decks, and the towering exhaust pipes pierce the black, stormy sky. A rope adorned with the flags of a dozen nations extends from the fore and aft masts.

The entrance to the bridge is to the west, and you can access the captain's cabin going southeast. Down leads back to the weather deck.
> se

> se

You are in the Captain's Cabin.
You can see a Walnut Desk.
You can go northwest.

The smell of the crisp sea air and light from the windows penetrates into the luxurious room. The captain's cabin is characterized by cherrywood paneling and a wax-shined wooden floor with a rug that squishes beneath your feet. There is the sort of elegance here that juxtaposes the captain's brusque manner, though his love for reading is apparent in the bookshelves built into the wall. A large bed sits on one side of the room, while the captain's desk and plush, upholstered chair occupies the other. There is a globe in a wooden cabinet with clawed feet in the corner.

The exit to the Navigation Deck is to the northwest.
