> d

You are in Mid Deck.
You can go down, up, south, southwest, west, east or southeast.

The mid deck is swathed in the most opulent materials, as many of the illustrious passengers spend their recreational time here. The walls are covered in gilded boiserie and thick crimson carpet cushions the linoleum hallways. Windows covered by velvet curtains look out onto the sea, and above the staircase leading to the upper decks hangs a grand portrait of the Prizessin Anna Alexia herself, the girl after whom the ship is named.

Going up or down will lead to the upper and lower decks, respectively. To the west is the Library, while the Dark Room for guests to develop photographs sits in the south west. To the east is gymnasium, and the game parlor occupies a room off the south east corridor. Finally, the rooms of the ship's staff such as the maids, the chefs, and so on, is located to the south.
> d

> d

You are in The Lower Deck.
You can go west, east, north, south or up.

The lower deck lacks the ostentatious displays of architecture and the niceties of the life of the gentry. Here, there are only slats of hard oak floor and metal walls painted white with blue stripes along the corners near the floor to guide the crew about. Brass intercom phones sit on the walls and crackle to life when orders come down from the bridge.

You can go back up the stairs to the mid deck. North leads to the brig, and south to the engine room. Your quarters are due west, and the ship's storage is to the east.
> w

> w

You are in The Crew Quarters.
You can see a Footlocker.
You can go east.

The crew quarters is a sparse cavern of a room full of uncomfortable bunk beds. This is where the crew sleeps and relaxes; metal tables for the tawdry sort of card games the passengers in the upper decks wouldn't think of playing, and the smell of rye is thick in the air. You can hear the discomfiting lullaby of the engine through the wall, and the Prinzessin creaks and groans as she fords through the sea. There are several third shift crewmembers in the room, sleeping off the morning gin. At the foot of each bed is an unassuming footlocker full of personal belongings, and one of your sculptures is sitting out on your bed.

East leads to the Lower Deck.
